        <div class="section movable text" id="66d6cf1c88b3444788bfe682dcd391bb" data-type="text" data-js-class="TextSection" data-dj-class="TextSection" data-layout-position="26">
    <div class="head">
        <div class="grip"></div>
        
        
            <h2 class="title" >
                Step 5: Alternative Methods of Quitting
            </h2>
        
    </div>
    <div class="notify"></div>
    <div class="body"  data-button-class="all">
        
<ul><li>While the techniques and methods listed above are the most common (and scientifically proven) ways to quit smoking, there are a number of alternative therapies and methods that people have developed for kicking the habit. Here are a few of the most common:<ref>http://www.health.com/health/condition-article/0,,20213799,00.html</ref>
</li></ul>
    </div>
</div>

     
        <div class="section movable text" id="f6eb795a0de643c5b01e80da1565ac01" data-type="text" data-js-class="TextSection" data-dj-class="TextSection" data-layout-position="27">
    <div class="head">
        <div class="grip"></div>
        
        
            <h2 class="title" >
                Hypnosis
            </h2>
        
    </div>
    <div class="notify"></div>
    <div class="body"  data-button-class="all">
        <p>
Hypnotherapy and Self-Hypnosis are methods that are used to help patients break through conditioned behaviors (such as smoking) and to replace them with new behaviors that don't involve harmful activities. During this process, patients are put into a deeply relaxed, sleep-like state of heightened awareness in which they are more susceptible to suggestions or prompting instructions. Certain keywords and phrases are introduced to the person under <a href="/hypnosis">hypnosis</a> that are aimed at reducing the patient's desire to smoke. There has been much debate about whether or not this method is effective after the hypnosis treatments have stopped. Success may also depend on each individuals natural susceptibility to hypnosis.<ref>http://www.health.com/health/condition-article/0,,20213799,00.html</ref>
</p>
    </div>
</div>

     
        <div class="section movable text" id="009b8a10d8fd4f0aaf2c92c0216e27f4" data-type="text" data-js-class="TextSection" data-dj-class="TextSection" data-layout-position="28">
    <div class="head">
        <div class="grip"></div>
        
        
            <h2 class="title" >
                Acupuncture
            </h2>
        
    </div>
    <div class="notify"></div>
    <div class="body"  data-button-class="all">
        <p>
<a href="/acupuncture">Acupuncture</a> is an alternative health technique in which fine needle points are inserted into the skin at different points. Proponents of acupuncture believe that placing needles at specific points on the body can help improve the patient's health and well-being. While acupuncture can lead to the release of endorphins into the body, producing a natural high, most health professionals do not believe that acupuncture is an effective long-term method for helping people quit smoking.<ref>http://www.health.com/health/condition-article/0,,20213799_2,00.html</ref>
</p>
    </div>
</div>

     
        <div class="section movable text" id="558c05bc68ed4116ac50e29534a0971b" data-type="text" data-js-class="TextSection" data-dj-class="TextSection" data-layout-position="29">
    <div class="head">
        <div class="grip"></div>
        
        
            <h2 class="title" >
                Aversion Therapy
            </h2>
        
    </div>
    <div class="notify"></div>
    <div class="body"  data-button-class="all">
        <p>
Aversion Therapy is a form of behavioral modification that attempts to reinforce the negative aspects of smoking cigarettes and create negative associations whenever a smoker lights up. Some forms of aversion therapy include the rapid and constant smoking of cigarettes - while concentrating on the unpleasant sensations of smoking, using silver acetate to give cigarettes an unpleasant taste, and even the administering of brief electrical shocks whenever a smoker tries to light a cigarette.<ref>http://www.psychologistworld.com/behavior/aversiontherapy.php</ref>
</p>
    </div>
</div>

     
        <div class="section movable text" id="1a9ae19fde364879b0030e73eefb72c8" data-type="text" data-js-class="TextSection" data-dj-class="TextSection" data-layout-position="30">
    <div class="head">
        <div class="grip"></div>
        
        
            <h2 class="title" >
                Facts About Nicotine Addiction
            </h2>
        
    </div>
    <div class="notify"></div>
    <div class="body"  data-button-class="all">
        
<ol><li>Nicotine is the psychoactive drug found in <a href="/tobacco">tobacco</a> products that, when ingested, gives the user a mildly euphoric feeling. It is also the chemical which users become addicted to.<ref>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2033559</ref>
</li><li>Research has shown that nicotine is as addictive as heroin, cocaine or alcohol.<ref>http://www1.umn.edu/perio/tobacco/nicaddct.html</ref>
</li><li>The average cigarette contains 1 to 2 mg of nicotine that, when ingested, is rapidly distributed to the brain within 10 seconds of inhalation.<ref>http://health.howstuffworks.com/wellness/smoking-cessation/hard-to-quit-smoking.htm/printable</ref>
</li><li>Nicotine increases the flow of <a href="/dopamine">dopamine</a> to the brain, which causes that "euphoric" feeling.<ref>http://www.webmd.com/smoking-cessation/nicotine-replacement-therapy-for-quitting-tobacco</ref>
</li></ol>
    </div>
</div>

     
        <div class="section movable text" id="a3a0db75f4d4487282ca9a59504e1539" data-type="text" data-js-class="TextSection" data-dj-class="TextSection" data-layout-position="31">
    <div class="head">
        <div class="grip"></div>
        
        
            <h2 class="title" >
                Disclaimer
            </h2>
        
    </div>
    <div class="notify"></div>
    <div class="body"  data-button-class="all">
        <p>
The content in this page is not a substitute for professional medical advice. Please contact your doctor before using the information presented here.
</p>
    </div>
</div>

     
